So `String.replaceFirst()` replaces the matched regex (in this case `^0+(?!$)`) The regex ^0+(?!$) matches sequences of one or more consecutive zeros at the beginning of a line or string, excluding any trailing zeros.

Then using `Double.parseDouble()` we can get the double value of the strings.

Then `String.format()` allows you to format strings depending on a specified locale. In this case `&quot;%.2f&quot;` means that the number should be formatted as a floating-point number (f) with two decimal places (.2). The reason the number are divided by 100 is to get the last two digits into the decimal places (eg. 4599 -&gt; 45.99).

`sumString` simply is the answer to the first part of your question--the 2 numbers added together replacing the dot from the double with an empty string.

The rest is just putting them both together into your specified format. 

```java
    public static String convertAndSum(String input1, String input2) {
        // Remove leading zeros from the inputs
        String number1 = input1.replaceFirst(&quot;^0+(?!$)&quot;, &quot;&quot;);
        String number2 = input2.replaceFirst(&quot;^0+(?!$)&quot;, &quot;&quot;);
        
        // Convert the inputs to double values
        double value1 = Double.parseDouble(number1);
        double value2 = Double.parseDouble(number2);
        
